Adcock, Datatec, Impala, Northam May Move: South African Equity Preview

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-08-02T22:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-02/adcock-datatec-impala-northam-south-african-equity-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or fall
in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last close.  The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index fell the most in two
weeks, dropping 385.53 points, or 1.2 percent, to 30,871.78 by
the 5 p.m. close of trading in Johannesburg.  Adcock Ingram Holdings Ltd. (AIP)  : Africa’s largest
over-the-counter drugs manufacturer said it appointed Andy Hall
as financial director and deputy chief executive officer with
effect from Aug. 1. Shares in the company fell 1.6 percent to 61
rand.  Capital Property Fund (CPL)  : The property-management
fund increased its distribution per unit for the six months to
June 30 by 11 percent to 31.36 cents. The stock fell 1.5 percent
to 8.47 rand.  Datatec Ltd. (DTC)  : The Johannesburg-based computer
services company is scheduled to hold its annual meeting of
shareholders. The stock gained 0.6 percent to 39.25 rand.  Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  : The world’s second-
largest producer of the metal meets labor unions to try and
resolve a wage dispute and avert a strike after its latest offer
was rejected. Shares in the company fell 1.3 percent to 169.79
rand.  Miranda Mineral Holdings Ltd. (MMH)  : The minerals
explorer said it appointed James Johnson as chief executive
officer with immediate effect, replacing Glen Poff, who has
resigned. Shares in the company fell 27 percent to 33 cents.  Northam Platinum Ltd. (NHM)  : The operator of the world’s
deepest platinum mine resumes wage talks with the National Union
of Mineworkers. Shares in the miner declined 1.9 percent to
35.03 rand.  Paladin Capital Ltd. (PLD)  : the private-equity group
controlled by PSG Group Ltd. said all conditions precedent to
the unbundling of Curro Holdings Ltd. have been fulfilled.
Shares in the company fell 3 percent to 2.90 rand.  Wilson Bayly Holmes-Ovcon Ltd. (WBO)  : The construction
company holds a general meeting of shareholders. Shares in
Wilson Bayly fell 2.1 percent to 103.75 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
